#: ../../your-cv.rst:5
msgid "Your CV"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:8
msgid "Your CV is a key document in your search for employment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:11
msgid "In the USA, a CV is called a *resum√©*."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:13
msgid ""
"You need to pay attention to *what your CV says*, but also *how it says "
"it*."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:17 ../../your-cv.rst:100
msgid "Contribute your perspective"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:19
msgid ""
"How did you write your CV? Have you had feedback from an employer on it? "
"What did they say? What was the best advice you had about your CV?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:21 ../../your-cv.rst:106
msgid ":ref:`How to contribute <contribute>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:23
msgid ""
"Many job applicants pay much more attention to the first of these, and "
"fail to appreciate how much the latter matters. They put a lot of care "
"into making sure it includes the things they think matter, but don't "
"always manage to make a good impression with it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:26
msgid ""
"Both those things matter, and arguably, what a busy reviewer will often "
"take away from your CV is an *impression*."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:28
msgid ""
"Another thing that many don't realise is that what an employer expects in"
" a CV can be very different, depending which part of the world they're "
"in. A CV that works for Germany might be much less successful for Canada "
"or India. We'll highlight some points where that might matter below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:30
msgid "But let's start with the content, which is more straightforward."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:33
msgid "What your CV should contain"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:36
msgid "Personal details"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:38
msgid "The basics: your full name, email address, telephone number."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:42
msgid "Your name"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:44
msgid "Your name might not be as simple as you think it is."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:46
msgid ""
"Someone from a European background could be named \"James Williams\" from"
" the day of his birth, all through school and life, in every context and "
"on every document, until the day he dies. As far as his name is "
"concerned, he has one simple and unchanging identity."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:48
msgid ""
"It's much more complex for many Africans, whose identities can be multi-"
"dimensional. Many Africans use different given names and even family "
"names depending on the context and whom they are talking to."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:50
msgid ""
"This can be a complete puzzle for non-Africans: why does this candidate "
"put the name *Miriam Ofili* on the application form, use something "
"different on her CV and she sign her email messages with something else "
"again?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:52
msgid ""
"For the purpose of presenting yourself in the world of international "
"business, it's recommended to choose a version of your name and stick to "
"it everywhere, as far as possible - in person, in your email address, on "
"LinkedIn."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:56
msgid "Prejudice and discrimination"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:58
msgid ""
"No doubt you have heard depressing stories of non-western candidates who "
"suddenly find better success when they use westernised versions of their "
"names, or hide their cultural identity by adopting a western name."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:62
msgid "Would you want to work in such an environment anyway?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:64
msgid "In one sense perhaps it's a lucky escape, but it's still wrong and unfair."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:66
msgid ""
"Without doubt it happens, but it's hard to know how much, or what to "
"advise."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:72
msgid "Your email address"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:74
msgid ""
"It helps if your email address appears to match your name - if Miriam "
"Ofili uses the email address afua.appiah@example.com, that's confusing - "
"even if there is a perfectly good reason for it that would be obvious to "
"a Ghanaian. And whatever address you use, let it look professional. Maybe"
" *coolzimboy98* was how you wanted the world to see you in high school, "
"but perhaps it's time to use something else for professional purposes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:78
msgid "Phone number"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:80
msgid ""
"Format your phone number, for example *+233 23 123456*, in such a way "
"that an international caller can enter it directly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:82
msgid ""
"Many in Africa will use have multiple phone numbers by default. List two "
"if you really have to, but better to keep it simple with one for an "
"international CV. (It's quite unlikely that anyone will actually call you"
" from abroad anyway.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:86
msgid "Other personal information"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:88
msgid ""
"*In general*, a western CV reviewer will not expect to see your full home"
" address, but it's recommended to include e.g. *Accra, Ghana* (that "
"provides useful information, such as time zone)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:90
msgid ""
"Few will have any need to see your photograph. Some (especially in North "
"America) will be rather surprised. Don't include a photograph unless the "
"company is based somewhere that photographs are expected, such as South "
"Africa. **Do your research** and find out what is expected."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:92
msgid ""
"There is almost *never* a good reason to mention your religion, age, "
"health or marital status."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:96
msgid "A personal statement"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:102
msgid "Do you agree with the advice on this page? What insight can you add?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:104
msgid ""
"In particular, what advice can you suggest on how to deal with ATS "
"(application tracking systems)?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:108
msgid ""
"This is optional. It can give a neat snapshot of you as person, but it "
"shouldn't be more than few words - perhaps one or two sentences - that "
"says who you are, where you want to be going, and why."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:110
msgid ""
"I am a recent computer science graduate. In my studies I saw directly how"
" low-literacy mobile health applications can bring tangible benefits to "
"marginalised rural communities. I want a career where I can contribute to"
" that too."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:112 ../../your-cv.rst:140
msgid "or:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:114
msgid ""
"An experienced Python developer and software coach with a passion for "
"standards and education. I especially enjoy working with and contributing"
" back to the open-source software projects and communities that gave me "
"my first opportunities."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:116
msgid ""
"**Don't** make it longer. **Don't** repeat things that you're going to "
"say elsewhere in the CV. **Don't** waste the space with disconnected and "
"fluffy words - even if it is a picture of you from a bit of distance, *it"
" needs to be solid and real*."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:120
msgid "Work history"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:122
msgid ""
"Always in reverse order, most recent at the top. Include dates and "
"places, and name the role."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:124
msgid ""
"**This space is precious**, so use it well. Don't waste it stating the "
"obvious. If you were working as a backend engineer, it's completely "
"useless to note that you \"wrote backend code\" (what else would you "
"expect a backend engineer to do?)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:128
msgid ""
"What you need to do here is :ref:`show the value you brought <vurt"
":interviewing-rules-demonstrate-value>` - what *you* contributed. Notice "
"how the examples below also name particular products and tools:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:130
msgid ""
"Created automated test cases (Pytest, Playwright) to address several "
"long-standing fragilities, that helped resolve them once and for all"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:132
#, python-format
msgid ""
"Rewrote all the tutorials for the product; we saw a 20% drop in common "
"new-user support requests as result"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:134
msgid "They keep showing what you did, and what value you brought in your work."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:136
msgid ""
"You can also mention one-off things; even if they weren't part of the "
"main story, they show what kind of person you are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:138
msgid ""
"Awarded \"Developer of the Month\" for completing a complex refactor of "
"our Postgres database code"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:142
msgid ""
"Spoke at <some conference> about some interesting scaling challenges as "
"we migrated MySQL from the cloud to bare metal"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:144
msgid ""
"**Weave your skills into this.** Seeing a skill mentioned in the context "
"of an achievement gives it a reality that listing it on its own never "
"will."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:148
msgid "Contracting, freelance, part-time roles"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:150
msgid ""
"A problem for many African candidates in particular is that they have a "
"**patchy work history**, that's simply a consequence of the limited and "
"unstable nature of the opportunities available in their economy."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:-1
msgid "Experience"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:154
msgid ""
"One candidate was told sternly by an interviewer that if he got the job, "
"he would \"need to stop all the side-hustles\" - as if the multiple "
"things he had on the go represented a choice rather than a necessity."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:156
msgid ""
"It can look bad on a CV - messy and hard to understand, and suggesting "
"that the candidate has neither focus-power nor commitment, with "
"overlapping jobs in different fields, with no sense of progression or "
"direction."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:158
msgid ""
"It might not be possible for you to avoid this, but ensure that you "
"describe them in a way that makes them look more coherent, and clearly "
"shows that they all belong under a heading of contracting or freelance "
"work. For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:160
msgid "*Contracting roles 2021-2025*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:162
msgid ""
"Technical documentation (Sphinx, RST), SEO, website maintenance (*<client"
" one>*)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:163
msgid "White papers, website content, technical articles (*<client two>*)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:164
msgid ""
"Data analysis (Pandas, NumPy, Jupyter) and presentation (Matplotlib, "
"Seaborn) (*<client three>*)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:165
msgid "Technical support, customer outreach, lead generation (*<client four>*)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:167
msgid ""
"In this case, you could make it look even more intentional: *Samuel Oni "
"Technical Communication (contracting roles 2021-2025)*. And why not? "
"Entire companies have a business model like this, such as agencies."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:171
msgid "Education and qualifications"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:173
msgid ""
"Once again, most recent at the top, including dates. Should you include "
"grades? If they're excellent (first class honours degree, for example) "
"then that is a good idea."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:175
msgid ""
"There's probably no need to include high school qualifications, unless "
"you are very early in your career (or you have some spectacular results "
"to share)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:177
msgid ""
"And, if you won a maths olympiad or received a national prize or award in"
" your studies, mention that."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:179
msgid ""
"Other qualifications and certifications can be useful, but be realistic "
"about how much value they are. It might be worth mentioning small online "
"courses, if only to show that you take professional development seriously"
" - e.g. perhaps:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:181
msgid ""
"Online certification/courses: Cybersecurity Basic and Advanced; Python "
"for HPC (Pluralsight), AWS Cloud level III"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:185
msgid "Volunteer and open-source work"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:187
msgid ""
"Don't underestimate the value of these - they show that you care enough "
"about something to do something for it. If you have contributed to open-"
"source, many companies will love that."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:189
msgid ""
"Don't forget that being the president of a university society, the "
"treasurer or chairperson of an association, the organiser of a big "
"student event are all good examples of work, that demonstrate your skills"
" and the ability to contribute value."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:191
msgid "The biggest and most impressive ones should always go first."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:195
msgid "Articles and research publications"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:197
msgid ""
"If you have some, they can be worth mentioning. Don't start listing every"
" single thing you wrote on your weblog, that looks silly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:201
msgid "Skills"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:203
msgid ""
"Be really careful with this. *Usually, it's a waste of space.* Most of "
"these should have *already* been woven into the descriptions of what you "
"did in the work history section, where they will have more meaning. On "
"the other hand, some experts recommend including it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:205
msgid "Consider:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:207
msgid ""
"Why bother mentioning Python as a skill if you already mentioned that you"
" spent five years as a Python engineer?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:208
msgid ""
"\"Problem solving\" - no reviewer is going to see that and think: "
"\"Great! We really need a problem-solver!\" The same goes for "
"\"Leadership\", \"Collaboration\", and so on."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:209
msgid ""
"If you are fresh out of university, don't list half a dozen programming "
"languages."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:210
msgid "\"MS Office\" is not a skill, and who cares, anyway?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:212
msgid ""
"The problem with these is that all you can do is *say* you have a certain"
" skill, and anyone can say that. You need to find ways to :ref:`show your"
" skills, don't just assert them <vurt:interviewing-rules-show>`, to make "
"it credible."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:216
msgid "Languages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:218
msgid ""
"One thing that African candidates often underestimate the value of is how"
" many languages they speak - it can be very impressive. It can be worth "
"mentioning those, for example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:220
msgid ""
"Language fluency: English (professional), French (basic), Arabic (basic),"
" Amharic (near-native), Tigrinya (native)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:222
msgid ""
"It's valuable not because you might find yourself needing to speak "
"Amharic or Tigrinya at work, but because it *demonstrates ability*. But "
"don't ever over-claim."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:226
msgid "Personal interests and achievements"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:228
msgid ""
"Are you a chess grandmaster? Are you a top gymnast, able to perform "
"amazing feats? Did you win a national short-story competition? Mention "
"it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:230
msgid ""
"Be a little bit specific. \"I enjoy reading\" doesn't tell anyone much, "
"but \"... and I am fascinated by the postcolonial literature of the "
"Indian subcontinent\" shows real interest and depth."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:232
msgid ""
"And, express what it means to you: \"Playing football with my local team "
"each weekend has been an important part of my life for several years\" "
"says something that \"I like playing football\" does not."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:234
msgid ""
"You never know when something that you like will trigger a spark of "
"recognition in an interviewer."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:241
msgid ""
"Take your time setting all these things down, in a simple document. At "
"first, be concerned only with the content, not how it will look, or how "
"to format it. Put down as much as you like - you will have to edit it "
"later to decide on the most important things to keep, but start with "
"everything."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:245
msgid "How to present your CV"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:248
msgid "Find a good template"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:250
msgid ""
"Are you a trained graphic designer? No? Then right now stop imagining "
"that you will do a good job of designing your CV: you will not. Instead, "
"take advantage of the fact that there are hundreds of excellent CV "
"templates out there that you can use."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:252
msgid ""
"Choose one you like. *Simple is almost always better*. Resist any urge to"
" go for something fancy."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:254
msgid ""
"Use the design carefully. Don't spoil it by clumsily pasting in new fonts"
" and text sizes, or messing up the spacing. Learn to use styles in your "
"word processor, so that you maintain the template's consistency."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:258
msgid "Decide on the length"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:260
msgid ""
"Now, you must understand that the expected length of a CV is different in"
" different parts of the world:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:262
msgid "in Europe and most of the west: two pages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:263
msgid "in the USA: a single page"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:264
msgid "on the Indian subcontinent: up to four pages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:266
msgid "So what are you going to do about that that?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:268
msgid ""
"It's exhausting to have to keep rewriting your CV. A sensible choice is "
"to default to two pages. Even if it seems a bit long to an American or a "
"bit short to an Indian, at least it's not wildly at variance with what "
"they expect."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:272
msgid "Cut it to size"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:274
msgid ""
"If you followed :ref:`the advice above <your-cv-everything>`, you will "
"have a lot of information to include. Now you'll have to go through the "
"painful process of deciding what not to include."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:276
msgid ""
"Go through each section, and decide what is the least important, least "
"impressive, least memorable thing. Remove it. Find ways to express what's"
" left more succinctly. And then repeat that process."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:278
msgid ""
"**You don't need to mention everything**. If you mention that you took "
"responsibility for the CI testing pipeline, a reader will infer that you "
"know - and did - a lot more besides, all related to testing. When you say"
" something that implies something else, then you won't need to mention "
"that thing explicitly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:280
msgid ""
"See :ref:`Be personal, specific and concrete  <vurt:interviewing-rules-"
"be-personal>` and :ref:`Show the parts, not the whole <vurt:interviewing-"
"rules-parts-not-wholes>`. Find ways to show more while saying less."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:282
msgid ""
"Avoid the temptation to \"cheat\" by reducing margins, font sizes and "
"spacing - you will start to make it look cramped."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:288
msgid "Customising your CV"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:290
msgid ""
"Consider customising your CV for an application, especially if you are "
"applying to quite different kinds of roles. It's reasonable to have "
"different versions of your CV."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:294
msgid ""
"**Always be truthful**, but pay attention to how your CV shows how you "
"are suited to the role."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:296
msgid ""
"An example of customising your CV might be to describe yourself as a "
"*Documentation-focused developer advocate* for one role and - perfectly "
"fairly - as *DevRel engineer/technical author* for another. You might re-"
"order or even redescribe skills and accomplishments, or omit some for "
"others."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:298
msgid ""
"This does take time, and if you do it in a hurry you risk making things "
"worse, not better. It won't help if you add spelling mistakes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:302
msgid "Automation and AI"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:304
msgid ""
"Many companies use applicant tracking systems (ATS) that automate CV "
"review completely, and make the first decision to advance or reject a "
"candidate. It is hard to know how well these systems handle all the "
"complexities and ambiguities of natural language, and how many candidates"
" fail to advance because the system failed to understand a CV properly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:306
msgid ""
"In any case, many now advise to write CVs not for a human reader, but for"
" a machine. They encourage stuffing the CV with keywords from the job "
"description."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:308
msgid ""
"It's not clear that this is good advice. *Possibly* it helps when the CV "
"is read by a machine, but to a human being it certainly looks mechanical "
"and wrong."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:310
#, python-format
msgid ""
"A similar kind of CV ugliness is produced by AI-powered CV builders. "
"There are many of these, but they seem to produce identical kind of "
"output. Many of them take the principle of :ref:`showing value <your-cv-"
"show-value>` to a ludicrous extreme, so that for example every line "
"conforms to a stereotype, complete with overblown language and unlikely-"
"sounding metrics (\"Spearheaded a re-organisation of the photocopier "
"paper, achieving a 17.3% improvement in organisational efficiency\")."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:312
msgid ""
"Don't fall for that, and don't fall for the dishonest self-description "
"that some of these sites encourage."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-cv.rst:314
msgid ""
"**Think for yourself**, and think about yourself and your abilities like "
"a human being. You need to be able to do that all the way through the "
"process of securing a job, and you'll need to do most of it while in "
"conversation with real human beings."
msgstr ""

